ubo.sps). It (1) reads /app/data/ohtsubo data.csv, (2) recodes a4 into a4r by reversing 1..7, (3) computes atot_recalc = a1+a2+a3+a4r+a5+a6, (4) checks vs precomputed atot if present, (5) splits participants by condition (1 vs 0), (6) computes descriptive stats, (7) runs Welch's t-test, (8) computes Cohen's d (pooled SD) and Welch df approximation, and (9) writes results to /app/data/analysis_ohtsubo_results.txt. This file is intended as the executed entrypoint for replication.\",\n        \"replication_data/analysis ohtsubo.sps\": \"Original SPSS syntax included for reference. It recodes a4 into a4r, computes atot by summing a1..a6 (with a4r), and runs a t-test GROUPS=condition(1 0) /VARIABLES=atot. The Python script replicates this logic.\",\n        \"replication_data/ohtsubo data.csv\": \"Primary dataset file containing participant responses and variables: a1..a6 (intimacy items), a4 (to be reversed), a4r (present in CSV but recomputed), atot (present but recomputed), condition (0/1), and demographics (age, sex, race). The Python script reads this file as its input from /app/data.\",\n        \"replication_data/Ohtsubo -score-2.sav\": \"SPSS binary data file of the same dataset; kept as an archival copy. Not required by the Python script but available if SPSS users want to cross-check.\",\n        \"replication_data/codebook.xlsx\": \"Excel codebook describing variables — helpful for mapping items to constructs; kept for reference. The binary Excel could be used to confirm item descriptions.\"\n      },\n      \"notes\": \"The original non-Python analysis script (SPSS) was translated into Python per requirements. All IO in the new Python script uses /app/data to match runtime environment. Ensure the CSV is present at /app/data/ohtsubo data.csv prior to execution. The script writes a results text file to /app/data/analysis_ohtsubo_results.txt for easy inspection. No other external data or network access is required. The Python script name ends with __py.py following the translation policy. If additional exploratory analyses are desired (e.g., include sex as covariate), augment the Python script accordingly.\"\n    },\n    \"docker_specs\": {\n      \"base_image\": \"python:3.10-slim\",\n      \"packages\": {\n        \"python\": [\n          \"pandas>=1.4.0\",\n          \"numpy>=1.22.0\",\n          \"scipy>=1.8.0\"\n        ],\n        \"other\": [\n          \"git\",\n          \"make\",\n          \"unzip\"\n        ]\n      },\n      \"hardware\": {\n        \"gpu_support\": \"false\",\n        \"min_gpu_memory_gb\": \"0\",\n        \"min_ram_gb\": \"2\"\n      },\n      \"volumes\": [\n        \"./data:/app/data\"\n      ]\n    },\n    \"analysis\": {\n      \"instructions\": \"1) Place ohtsubo data.csv at /app/data/ohtsubo data.csv. 2) Start container from python:3.10-slim with the repository mounted such that /app/data contains the dataset. 3) Install required Python packages (pip install pandas numpy scipy). 4) Run the entrypoint script: python /path/to/repository/data/original/37/input/replication_data/analysis_ohtsubo__py.py. 5) Inspect output file at /app/data/analysis_ohtsubo_results.txt for descriptive statistics, t-statistic, p-value, Welch df, and Cohen's d. 6) Compare sign and statistical significance with the original reported effect (initial_details.txt and post_registration.json report t(27)=5.91, p<.001, d=2.20 for Study 2a; note that the current dataset has n=41 and may produce different values).\",\n      \"comparison_metrics\": \"Compare direction of mean difference (mean_condition1 > mean_condition0), t-statistic and p-value, and Cohen's d effect size. Report whether effect is statistically significant at alpha=0.05 and whether the effect size matches the same direction and magnitude range reported in the original study. Also compare sample sizes (n) and note deviations.\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n","overwrite":true}) 
